Prosper Loan Data Exploration.¶

by Winnie Minayo¶

Introduction¶

The prosper loan dataset is one that contains the loan information of the prosper organisation. The data ranges from the details of people who have taken loans, the amount of loans taken, those paid and unpaid, and the returns of the organisation.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The prosper loan data consists of 113,937 rows and 81 columns. The datatypes of the columns range from integers, float, bool to string. There are some missing values in a number of columns. There are variable such as loan status, employment status and income range that are categorical in nature.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features in this dataset according to me are the loan status and estimated return. These two variables are able to show the amount of loans that have been paid and yet to be paid and whether any profits were being made at that time.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Variables such as the borrower APR, borrower rate, employment status, and income range will help understand the factors that affect the loan status of individuals. I will also explore the prosper principal borrowed and on time prosper payments and their effects on returns.

# convert loan status, employment status, and income range into ordered categorical types
ord_loan_var_dict = {'LoanStatus': ['Completed', 'Current', 'Past Due (1-15 days)', 'Defaulted','Chargedoff', 'Past Due (16-30 days)', 'Cancelled','Past Due (61-90 days)', 'Past Due (31-60 days)',
       'Past Due (91-120 days)', 'FinalPaymentInProgress','Past Due (>120 days)'],
                    'EmploymentStatus': ['Self-employed', 'Employed', 'Not available', 'Full-time', 'Other','Not employed', 'Part-time', 'Retired'],
                    'IncomeRange': ['Not Employed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74,999','$75,000-99,000','$100,000+','Not Displayed']}

for var in ord_loan_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ord_loan_var_dict[var])
    newloan_df[var] = newloan_df[var].astype(ordered_var)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The loan status was categorical with a high number indicating that the loans were current and very few were past due. The borrower rate, borrower APR and the estimated return variables were normally distriuted with a similar range. On the other hand the on time prosper payments and the prosper principal borrowed showed a skewed distribution and a log transformation was applied to get more insight to the distribution of the data. The employment status and the income range were also categorical in nature.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There were null values observed in some of the columns but they were indicative of no past record and so according to me they were not affecting the analysis in any negative way. To sample the data, the null rows were dropped off from the dataset from the selected variables.

It was an interesting fact that the interest rates incurred by the borrower did not affect the principal amount borrowed.

Conclusions¶

Different plots were used to visualize the variable, their distributions and their relationships. It can be noted that the employment status and income range were factors that were considered when issuing of loans and the borrower apr and rates heavily influenced the estimated returns.
